{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2814144a-fbc1-4ca6-bb11-2023f9b3fec9","content":"No worries that the file isn't here — the configuration is straightforward.\n\nCreate a `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- Your MCP server must read JSON-RPC messages from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout**. Make sure any logging goes to **stderr**, not stdout.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command`/`args` with the path to the executable.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat in agent mode (`@workspace`) and it will auto-discover the server's tools.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"52a843d2-3d2e-4241-b68f-5e25e684bac5","outputTokens":263,"requestId":"AC0F:21DE79:B0DFC7:DC9C9D:6A012D18"},"id":"3e14cf5c-e0eb-46ce-87f3-7c8e56491579","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:13:04.344Z","parentId":"080b7168-01a6-4118-ba9a-009dadf2ccd2"}
